  "description": "Constitutionalism is the principle that government power should be structured and limited by a foundational legal document — a constitution — that is harder to change than ordinary law. The constitution defines the organs of government, distributes power among them, and specifies the rights that government may not violate. Ordinary legislation must conform to the constitution; if it doesn\u0026rsquo;t, it can be struck down through judicial review.\nConstitutions do two things that are in tension. They empower — by creating institutions and authorizing them to act. And they constrain — by setting limits on what those institutions may do. The balance between empowerment and constraint varies: some constitutions grant broad emergency powers; others enumerate rights so specific that they restrict government action even in crisis. The U.S. Constitution\u0026rsquo;s Bill of Rights operates primarily as constraint; the preamble to the French Constitution of 1958 operates primarily as empowerment, defining the republic\u0026rsquo;s values and mission.\n",
